Absolutely! Here's a clear explanation of the difference between shallow copy and deep copy in JavaScript:

ğŸ”¹ Shallow Copy
A shallow copy copies only the top-level properties of an object.
If a property is an object or array, only the reference is copiedâ€”not the actual nested structure.

Example:
const original = { name: "Mahi", skills: ["JS", "React"] };
const shallow = { ...original };

shallow.skills.push("Node.js");
console.log(original.skills); // ["JS", "React", "Node.js"] â—
âœ… Top-level copied
âŒ Nested objects/arrays are still shared

ğŸ”¹ Deep Copy
A deep copy creates a completely independent clone, including all nested objects or arrays.

Example:
const original = { name: "Mahi", skills: ["JS", "React"] };
const deep = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(original));

deep.skills.push("Node.js");
console.log(original.skills); // ["JS", "React"] âœ…
âœ… Everything is copied
âœ… No shared references

âš ï¸ Note:
JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj)) is a common deep copy method, but:

âŒ Fails with functions, undefined, Date, Map, etc.

For complex cases, use libraries like:

Lodash: _.cloneDeep(obj)

In a deep copy, all levels of the object are duplicated â€” so:

ğŸ‘‰ Changes in the deep copy do NOT affect the original object, and vice versa.

const original = { name: "Mahi", info: { age: 25 } };

// Deep copy
const copy = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(original));

// Modify deep copy
copy.info.age = 30;

console.log(original.info.age); // â 25 (âœ… unchanged)
console.log(copy.info.age);     // â 30
